                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d487">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/1085: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-02-10T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 10, 1933—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>25. Brazilian Government apparently does not realize urgency of situation. If it
                    is going to take action in this matter it should not delay. <pb facs="0558"
                        n="470" xml:id="pg_470"/> Following telegram from Bogotá shows difficulty of
                    situation there. (Here quote No. 29, February 9, 9 p.m. from Bogotá).</p>
                <p>The suggestion referred to in Caffery’s No. 25 of February 4, 3 p.m. is as
                    follows: “Peru would turn over Leticia at once to Brazil; conference would start
                    at once Rio de Janeiro and no matter what result of conference Brazil would
                    deliver Leticia to Colombia at expiration of 60 days.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
